# Check Subtree in a Binary Tree

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* A subtree match can start at any node in the main tree, so the natural idea is to try every node as a possible starting point.
* For each starting point, we check whether both trees are exactly the same in structure and values.
* This always works because a subtree is valid only when every matching node and every missing child line up perfectly, but it can be slow because the same comparisons may be repeated many times.

### Approach

* Compare the current node of the main tree with the root of the smaller tree and check whether both trees are exactly identical.
* If they are not identical, move to the left child of the main tree and repeat the same check.
* If still not found, move to the right child of the main tree and repeat again.
* Return true as soon as any matching subtree is found, otherwise return false after the full tree is explored.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
isSameTree(s, t) {
    /* If both nodes are empty, this part of both trees matches perfectly */
    if (!s && !t) {

        /* Both trees ended together, so they are identical here */
        return true
    }

    /* If one node is missing or the values differ, the trees do not match */
    if (!s || !t || s->data != t->data) {

        /* A mismatch means these two trees cannot be identical */
        return false
    }

    /* Check whether both left subtrees and both right subtrees match */
    return isSameTree(s->left, t->left) && isSameTree(s->right, t->right)
}

isSubtree(root, subRoot) {
    /* If the main tree is empty, there is no place left to search */
    if (!root) {

        /* No matching subtree can be found from an empty tree */
        return false
    }

    /* Check whether the subtree starting at the current node matches fully */
    if (isSameTree(root, subRoot)) {

        /* Exact match found, so the smaller tree is a subtree */
        return true
    }

    /* Search for the same subtree inside the left or right side of the main tree */
    return isSubtree(root->left, subRoot) || isSubtree(root->right, subRoot)
}
```

