### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n * m)`**

  * We may try every node of the main tree as a possible starting point for the subtree match.
  * For each such starting point, the equality check can visit all nodes of the smaller tree in the worst case.
  * The dominant term is `O(n * m)` because these two costs can combine across the full search.

* **Space Complexity: `O(h1 + h2)`**

  * The recursive search over the main tree uses stack space up to its height, and the tree comparison adds stack space up to the height of the smaller tree.
  * Aside from the recursive call stack, only constant extra variables are used, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(h1 + h2)`.

## Solution 2: Knuth-Morris-Pratt Algorithm (KMP)

### Intuition

* Instead of comparing the smaller tree again and again at many nodes, we can turn both trees into strings that preserve both values and shape.
* Once both trees are written in this form, the problem becomes finding whether one string appears inside the other.
* Null markers and value separators are important here, because without them different tree shapes could accidentally look the same.

### Approach

* Convert both trees into preorder strings while also writing markers for missing children.
* Add a separator before every value so that different numbers do not merge into the same text pattern.
* Build the matching table for the smaller string using the KMP pattern matching method.
* Scan the larger string with KMP to check whether the smaller serialized tree appears inside it.
* Return true if a match is found, otherwise return false.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
serialize(node, treeStr) {
    /* Write a marker for an empty child so tree structure is preserved */
    if (node == nullptr) {

        /* Store the null marker and stop this path */
        treeStr += "#"
        return
    }

    /* Add a separator before the value to avoid text ambiguity */
    treeStr += "^"

    /* Append the current node value to the serialized tree */
    treeStr += to_string(node->data)

    /* Serialize the left subtree to keep preorder order */
    serialize(node->left, treeStr)

    /* Serialize the right subtree to keep preorder order */
    serialize(node->right, treeStr)
}

kmp(needle, haystack) {
    /* Measure both strings before starting pattern matching */
    m = needle.length()
    n = haystack.length()

    /* If the pattern is longer, matching is impossible */
    if (n < m) {

        /* Return failure immediately for this invalid case */
        return false
    }

    /* Create the longest prefix suffix table for the pattern */
    lps[0...m-1] = 0

    /* Track the current best prefix length */
    prev = 0

    /* Start building the table from the second character */
    i = 1

    /* Fill the prefix table for the whole pattern */
    while (i < m) {

        /* If characters match, extend the current prefix */
        if (needle[i] == needle[prev]) {
            prev += 1
            lps[i] = prev
            i += 1
        }

        /* If no prefix is available, this position gets zero */
        else if (prev == 0) {
            lps[i] = 0
            i += 1
        }

        /* Otherwise, fall back to the previous valid prefix */
        else {
            prev = lps[prev - 1]
        }
    }

    /* Start scanning the main string using the prefix table */
    haystackPointer = 0
    needlePointer = 0

    /* Continue while there are characters left in the main string */
    while (haystackPointer < n) {

        /* If current characters match, move both pointers */
        if (haystack[haystackPointer] == needle[needlePointer]) {
            needlePointer += 1
            haystackPointer += 1

            /* Full pattern matched inside the main string */
            if (needlePointer == m) {
                return true
            }
        }

        /* If mismatch happens at the beginning, move the main pointer */
        else if (needlePointer == 0) {
            haystackPointer += 1
        }

        /* Otherwise, reuse previous match information from the table */
        else {
            needlePointer = lps[needlePointer - 1]
        }
    }

    /* Pattern never appeared inside the main string */
    return false
}

isSubtree(root, subRoot) {
    /* Start with an empty serialization for the main tree */
    r = ""

    /* Convert the main tree into a preorder string */
    serialize(root, r)

    /* Start with an empty serialization for the smaller tree */
    s = ""

    /* Convert the smaller tree into a preorder string */
    serialize(subRoot, s)

    /* Check whether the smaller serialization appears in the larger one */
    return kmp(s, r)
}
