# Find Median in Data Stream

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* The simplest idea is to keep all numbers in sorted order, because the median is always taken from the middle of a sorted list.
* After each new number arrives, we sort the whole collection again and then read the middle position.
* This method is easy to build and always gives the correct answer, but sorting again and again becomes expensive.

### Approach

* Store every incoming number in a list.
* After each insertion, sort the entire list in increasing order.
* If the total count is odd, return the middle element.
* If the total count is even, return the average of the two middle elements.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
MedianTracker {
    /* global variable (array to store the numbers) */
    numbers
    /* Cunstructor */
    MedianTracker() {

    }
    /* Insert the new value and restore sorted order for easy median lookup */
    insertNum(x) {
        /* Add the incoming value to the stored list */
        numbers.push_back(x)
        /* Sort the full list so middle positions stay valid */
        sort(numbers)
    }

    /* Return the median from the current sorted list */
    findMedian() {
        /* Count how many values are stored right now */
        n = len(numbers)
        /* If the stream is empty, return a sentinel value */
        if n == 0 {
            /* No median exists yet */
            return -1
        }

        /* If the count is odd, the single middle value is the median */
        if n % 2 != 0 {
            /* Return the middle element */
            return numbers[n / 2]
        }

        /* Otherwise, use the two middle values */
        else {
            /* Read the left middle element */
            mid1 = numbers[n / 2 - 1]
            /* Read the right middle element */
            mid2 = numbers[n / 2]
            /* Return the average of both middle elements */
            return (mid1 + mid2) / 2.0
        }
    }
}
