### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n log n)`**

  * Inserting a new value appends it and then sorts all stored elements, which takes `O(n log n)` for the current stream size.
  * Reading the median only checks one or two middle positions, which takes `O(1)`.
  * The dominant term is `O(n log n)` because sorting the full list is the most expensive operation.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The list stores every inserted value, so memory grows with the size of the stream.
  * Only constant extra variables are used while sorting and reading the median, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(n)`.

## Solution 2: Better Approach

### Intuition

* We still want the numbers to stay sorted, but sorting the whole list after every insertion does extra work.
* A better idea is to find the correct position of the new number first and place it directly there.
* This saves the full re-sorting step, although shifting elements in the list still takes time.

### Approach

* Keep the list sorted at all times.
* Use binary search to find where the new number should be placed.
* Insert the new number at that exact position.
* Read the middle element or the two middle elements to get the median.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
MedianTracker {
    numbers
    /* Cunstructor */
    MedianTracker() {

    }
    /* Insert the new value into its correct sorted position */
    insertNum(x) {

        /* Find the index where the value should be placed */
        position = binarySearch(x)

        /* Insert the value so the list remains sorted */
        numbers.insert(position, x)
    }

    /* Find the insertion position using binary search */
    binarySearch(x) {

        /* Start with the full searchable range */
        low = 0

        /* Set the right boundary to the last stored index */
        high = len(numbers) - 1

        /* Narrow the range until the insertion position is found */
        while low <= high {

            /* Check the middle of the current range */
            mid = (low + high) / 2

            /* If the middle value matches, this position is valid */
            if numbers[mid] == x {

                /* Return the matching position */
                return mid
            }

            /* If the middle value is smaller, search on the right side */
            else if numbers[mid] < x {

                /* Move the left boundary forward */
                low = mid + 1
            }

            /* Otherwise, search on the left side */
            else {

                /* Move the right boundary backward */
                high = mid - 1
            }
        }

        /* Return the first valid insertion position */
        return low
    }

    /* Return the median from the current sorted list */
    findMedian() {

        /* Count how many values are stored right now */
        n = len(numbers)

        /* If the stream is empty, return a sentinel value */
        if n == 0 {

            /* No median exists yet */
            return -1
        }

        /* If the count is odd, the middle value is the median */
        if n % 2 != 0 {

            /* Return the middle element */
            return numbers[n / 2]
        }

        /* Otherwise, use the two middle values */
        else {

            /* Read the left middle element */
            mid1 = numbers[n / 2 - 1]

            /* Read the right middle element */
            mid2 = numbers[n / 2]

            /* Return the average of both middle elements */
            return (mid1 + mid2) / 2.0
        }
    }
}
