### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * Binary search finds the insertion position in `O(log n)`, but placing the value inside an array-based list may shift many elements.
  * Reading the median only accesses one or two middle positions, which takes `O(1)`.
  * The dominant term is `O(n)` because insertion into the middle of the list is costlier than the search step.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The sorted list stores every inserted value, so memory grows with the size of the stream.
  * Only constant extra variables are used during searching and median lookup, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(n)`.

## Solution 3: Optimal Approach

### Intuition

* The median depends only on the split around the middle, not on the full sorted order of all values.
* So we keep the smaller half on one side and the larger half on the other side.
* If these two sides stay balanced, the median is either the top of the left side or the average of both tops.
* This gives fast updates while keeping the answer ready at all times.

### Approach

* Keep the smaller half of the numbers in a max-heap and the larger half in a min-heap.
* Insert the new number into the correct heap based on the current middle split.
* Rebalance the heaps so they stay equal in size or the left heap has one extra element.
* If the total count is odd, return the top of the left heap.
* If the total count is even, return the average of the two heap tops.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
MedianTracker {

    maxHeap
    minHeap
    /* Cunstructor*/
    MedianTracker() {

    }
    /* Insert the new value into one of the two heaps */
    insertNum(x) {

        /* If the left heap is empty or the value belongs to the smaller half, push it there */
        if len(maxHeap) == 0 or x <= maxHeap.top() {

            /* Add the new value to the left heap */
            maxHeap.push(x)
        }

        /* Otherwise, the value belongs to the larger half */
        else {

            /* Add the new value to the right heap */
            minHeap.push(x)
        }

        /* If the left heap has grown too large, move one value to the right heap */
        if len(maxHeap) > len(minHeap) + 1 {

            /* Move the largest value from the smaller half */
            minHeap.push(maxHeap.top())

            /* Remove that value from the left heap */
            maxHeap.pop()
        }

        /* If the right heap becomes larger, move one value back to the left heap */
        else if len(minHeap) > len(maxHeap) {

            /* Move the smallest value from the larger half */
            maxHeap.push(minHeap.top())

            /* Remove that value from the right heap */
            minHeap.pop()
        }
    }

    /* Return the median from the tops of the two heaps */
    findMedian() {

        /* If both heaps are empty, return a sentinel value */
        if len(maxHeap) == 0 and len(minHeap) == 0 {

            /* No median exists yet */
            return -1
        }

        /* If the left heap has one extra value, its top is the median */
        if len(maxHeap) > len(minHeap) {

            /* Return the middle value */
            return maxHeap.top()
        }

        /* Otherwise, average the two middle values */
        else {

            /* Return the average of both heap tops */
            return (maxHeap.top() + minHeap.top()) / 2.0
        }
    }
}
