# Maximum Subarray Product

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* The most direct idea is to check every possible subarray and compute its product.
* Since every subarray is considered, the largest product will definitely be found.
* This works correctly, but it is slow because the same elements get multiplied again and again for different subarrays.

### Approach

* Pick every possible starting position of a subarray.
* For each starting position, pick every possible ending position.
* For each chosen range, multiply all elements inside that subarray.
* Keep updating the largest product seen so far.
* Return the largest product after checking all subarrays.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
/* Check every possible subarray and return the largest product */
maxProduct(arr) {

    /* Store the size of the array so all positions can be visited */
    n = arr.size()

    /* Start with the smallest possible answer so any valid product can replace it */
    ans = -∞

    /* Try every possible starting index of a subarray */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Try every possible ending index for the current start */
        for j = i to n - 1 {

            /* Reset the product before multiplying elements in the chosen subarray */
            product = 1

            /* Multiply all elements from the current start to the current end */
            for k = i to j {

                /* Extend the current subarray product by one element */
                product = product * arr[k]
            }

            /* Update the best answer if this subarray product is larger */
            ans = max(ans, product)
        }
    }

    /* Return the largest product found among all subarrays */
    return ans
}
```

