### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n^3)`**

  * The first loop chooses the starting position, and the second loop chooses the ending position of each subarray.
  * The third loop multiplies all elements inside that chosen subarray, which can take up to `O(n)` time.
  * The dominant term is `O(n^3)` because three nested loops may each run up to `n` times.

* **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  * The algorithm uses only a few extra variables to store the answer and the running product.
  * No additional array, map, or helper structure is created.
  * Total space used is `O(1)`.

## Solution 2: Better Approach

### Intuition

* In the previous method, the same subarray product is recomputed from scratch many times.
* A better idea is to fix a starting point and keep extending the subarray one element at a time, updating the product as we go.
* This removes one full loop, so it is faster while still checking every possible subarray.

### Approach

* Pick every possible starting position of a subarray.
* Begin with a product value of one for that starting position.
* Extend the subarray step by step toward the right and multiply the new element into the running product.
* After each extension, compare the current product with the best answer found so far.
* Return the largest product after all starting positions are processed.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
/* Build products incrementally for every starting index and return the largest one */
maxProduct(arr) {

    /* Store the size of the array so all starting points can be processed */
    n = arr.size()

    /* Start with the smallest possible answer so any valid product can replace it */
    ans = -∞

    /* Try every possible starting index of a subarray */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Reset the running product for the new starting index */
        product = 1

        /* Extend the subarray from the current start toward the right */
        for j = i to n - 1 {

            /* Include the new element in the running product */
            product = product * arr[j]

            /* Update the best answer if the current product is larger */
            ans = max(ans, product)
        }
    }

    /* Return the largest product found among all subarrays */
    return ans
}
```

