## Solution 3: Bit Counting Modulo Three

### Intuition

* Every repeated number contributes its set bits in groups of three.

* If we count set bits position by position, the remainder after dividing by three tells us which bits belong to the single value.

* This lets us rebuild the answer directly without storing frequencies, so it is both fast and memory efficient.

* The only extra care is handling the sign bit correctly so negative numbers are also reconstructed properly.

### Approach

* Check all 32 bit positions one by one.

* For each bit position, count how many array values have that bit set.

* Use the remainder after division by three to decide whether that bit should be present in the answer.

* Rebuild the final number from these remaining bits.

* Convert the result back to a signed 32 bit value when needed.

### Pseudocode

```customtext
singleNumber(arr) {
    /* Store the answer built from bit counts */
    ans = 0

    /* Check every bit position */
    for i = 0 to 31 {

        /* Count how many numbers have the current bit set */
        bitSum = 0

        for each num in arr {

            /* Read the current bit using unsigned form */
            maskNum = unsigned form of num
            bitSum = bitSum + ((maskNum >> i) & 1)
        }

        /* Keep this bit if it does not belong to a group of three */
        if bitSum % 3 != 0 {
            ans = ans | (1 << i)
        }
    }

    /* Convert to signed 32 bit value if the sign bit is set */
    if ans >= (1 << 31) {
        ans = ans - (1 << 32)
    }

    /* Return the single element */
    return ans
}
```

