# Substrings with all 3 characters

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* A direct idea is to fix the starting position and keep extending the substring until all three letters appear.

* The moment a substring contains all three letters, every longer substring from the same start will also be valid.

* This makes counting simple, but many characters may get checked again for different starting positions, so the method is slow.

### Approach

* Try every position as the starting point of a substring.
* Keep extending that substring to the right and record whether each of the three letters has appeared.
* As soon as all three letters are present, add all possible endings from that point to the answer.
* Repeat the same process for every starting position.

### Pseudocode

```customtext
countSubstringsWithAllABC(s) {
    /* Store the string length and the final count */
    n = length of s
    ans = 0

    /* Try every starting position */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Reset the presence tracker for the new start */
        seen = [0, 0, 0]

        /* Extend the substring to the right */
        for j = i to n - 1 {

            /* Mark the current character as present */
            seen[s[j] - 'a'] = 1

            /* Count all valid endings once all three characters appear */
            if seen[0] + seen[1] + seen[2] == 3 {
                ans = ans + (n - j)
                break
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the total number of valid substrings */
    return ans
}
```

