## Solution 3: Optimal Approach

### Intuition

* For any ending position, a substring is valid only if all three letters have appeared somewhere before or at that point.
* So we only need to remember the most recent position of each letter.
* The earliest among those three positions tells how many starting points can form a valid substring ending there.
* This gives a one-pass solution with constant extra memory.

### Approach

* Keep track of the latest position where each of the three letters was seen.
* Move through the string from left to right and update the latest position of the current letter.
* Find the earliest among the three latest positions.
* Add the number of valid starting points up to that earliest position to the answer.
* Repeat this for every character in the string.

### Pseudocode

```customtext
countSubstringsWithAllABC(s) {
    /* Store the string length, last seen positions, and answer */
    n = length of s
    last = [-1, -1, -1]
    ans = 0

    /* Process each character from left to right */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Update the latest position of the current character */
        last[s[i] - 'a'] = i

        /* Count valid substrings ending at the current position */
        earliest = minimum of last[0], last[1], and last[2]
        ans = ans + earliest + 1
    }

    /* Return the total number of valid substrings */
    return ans
}
```

