# Count Good Subarrays

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* The simplest idea is to check every possible subarray and count how many odd numbers it contains.
* For each starting position, we keep extending the subarray to the right and update the odd count as we go.
* This always finds every valid subarray, but it becomes slow because many overlapping subarrays are checked again and again.

### Approach

* Start from each possible position in the array.
* Extend the subarray one element at a time toward the right.
* Increase the odd count whenever the current element is odd.
* Add to the answer whenever the odd count becomes equal to the required value.
* Stop extending from the current start once the odd count becomes greater than the required value.

### Pseudocode

```customtext
countGoodSubarrays(arr, k) {
    /* Store the size of the array and initialize the answer */
    n = arr.size()
    ans = 0

    /* Try every possible starting position */
    for start = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Reset odd count for the current starting position */
        oddCount = 0

        /* Extend the subarray toward the right */
        for end = start to n - 1 {

            /* Update the odd count if the current element is odd */
            if arr[end] % 2 == 1 {
                oddCount = oddCount + 1
            }

            /* Count this subarray if it has exactly k odd numbers */
            if oddCount == k {
                ans = ans + 1
            }

            /* No need to continue if the odd count already exceeded k */
            if oddCount > k {
                break
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the total number of good subarrays */
    return ans
}
```

