# Summing Ranges within Subarrays

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* Every subarray has one smallest value and one largest value, so its range is just their difference.
* A simple way to get all answers is to fix a starting position and keep extending the subarray one element at a time.
* While extending, we can keep updating the smallest and largest values instead of recomputing them from scratch, but we still check all subarrays, so this becomes slow for large inputs.

### Approach

* Start from each position of the array as the beginning of a subarray.
* Keep extending the ending position one step at a time toward the right.
* While extending, continuously track the current smallest and largest values in that subarray.
* Add the difference between the current largest and smallest values to the final sum.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```customtext
/* Compute the range of every possible subarray by expanding from each starting position */
sumOfSubarrayRanges(arr) {

    /* Store the size of the array so the loops know their bounds */
    n = arr.size()

    /* Start with zero because no subarray has been processed yet */
    sum = 0

    /* Pick each index as the starting point of a subarray */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Start with extreme values so the first element updates both correctly */
        mini = ∞
        maxi = -∞

        /* Extend the current subarray from the starting point to the right */
        for j = i to n - 1 {

            /* Update the smallest value seen in the current subarray */
            mini = min(mini, arr[j])

            /* Update the largest value seen in the current subarray */
            maxi = max(maxi, arr[j])

            /* Add the range of the current subarray to the final answer */
            sum = sum + (maxi - mini)
        }
    }

    /* All subarray ranges have been added, so return the total */
    return sum
}
```

