# Boundary Traversal of Binary Tree

## Solution

### Intuition

* The boundary of a binary tree can be seen as three parts: the left edge, all leaf nodes, and the right edge taken in reverse order.
* To avoid repeating nodes, we should not include leaf nodes while collecting the left and right boundaries, because they will already be added in the leaf traversal.
* This works because every boundary node belongs to exactly one of these parts, and combining them in this order gives the required anti-clockwise traversal.

### Approach

* Start with the root node if it is not a leaf.
* Traverse down the left side and collect only non-leaf boundary nodes.
* Traverse the whole tree and collect all leaf nodes from left to right.
* Traverse down the right side, collect only non-leaf boundary nodes in a temporary list, and add them in reverse order at the end.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
isLeaf(node) {
    /* A node is a leaf only when both children are absent */
    if node->left == null && node->right == null {

        /* Return true because this node has no children */
        return true
    }

    /* Return false because this node is not a leaf */
    return false
}

leftBoundary(root, ans) {
    /* Start from the left child because the root is handled separately */
    cur = root->left

    /* Keep moving along the left boundary */
    while cur {

        /* Add the current node only if it is not a leaf */
        if !isLeaf(cur) {

            /* Store this boundary node in the answer */
            ans.push_back(cur->data)
        }

        /* Prefer moving left to stay on the boundary */
        if cur->left {

            /* Move to the left child */
            cur = cur->left
        }
        else {

            /* Move to the right child when left child is absent */
            cur = cur->right
        }
    }
}

leafNodes(root, ans) {
    /* Stop recursion when the current node is absent */
    if root == null {

        /* Nothing to add from an empty subtree */
        return
    }

    /* Add the node if it is a leaf */
    if isLeaf(root) {

        /* Store this leaf in left to right order */
        ans.push_back(root->data)
    }

    /* Recurse on the left subtree to collect its leaves */
    leafNodes(root->left, ans)

    /* Recurse on the right subtree to collect its leaves */
    leafNodes(root->right, ans)
}

rightBoundary(root, ans) {
    /* Start from the right child because the root is handled separately */
    cur = root->right

    /* Use a temporary list so the final order can be reversed */
    temp = empty list

    /* Keep moving along the right boundary */
    while cur {

        /* Add the current node only if it is not a leaf */
        if !isLeaf(cur) {

            /* Store this node temporarily */
            temp.push_back(cur->data)
        }

        /* Prefer moving right to stay on the boundary */
        if cur->right {

            /* Move to the right child */
            cur = cur->right
        }
        else {

            /* Move to the left child when right child is absent */
            cur = cur->left
        }
    }

    /* Add the right boundary in reverse to maintain anti-clockwise order */
    for i = temp.size() - 1 to 0 {

        /* Append each stored node into the final answer */
        ans.push_back(temp[i])
    }
}

boundaryTraversal(root) {
    /* Create the final list that will store the boundary traversal */
    ans = empty list

    /* Handle the empty tree case immediately */
    if root == null {

        /* Return the empty answer */
        return ans
    }

    /* Add the root first only when it is not a leaf */
    if !isLeaf(root) {

        /* Store the root as the starting boundary node */
        ans.push_back(root->data)
    }

    /* Collect the left boundary excluding leaf nodes */
    leftBoundary(root, ans)

    /* Collect all leaf nodes from left to right */
    leafNodes(root, ans)

    /* Collect the right boundary in reverse order */
    rightBoundary(root, ans)

    /* Return the completed boundary traversal */
    return ans
}
