# Vertical Order Traversal of Binary Tree

## Solution

### Intuition

* Each node belongs to a vertical line, so we need a way to group nodes column by column from left to right.
* While grouping nodes in the same column, we must also keep them ordered from top to bottom, and if two nodes share the exact same position, the smaller value should come first.
* A level-order traversal is a natural fit here because it visits every node once while letting us track both its row and its column.
* The main extra work comes from storing nodes in sorted order by their position before building the final traversal.

### Approach

* Start a breadth-first traversal from the root and treat it as being at row zero and column zero.
* For every visited node, store its value using its column first and its row second so nodes are grouped by vertical line and depth.
* When moving to the left child, go one row lower and one column left; when moving to the right child, go one row lower and one column right.
* After the traversal, process columns from left to right and rows from top to bottom.
* If multiple values appear at the same row and column, sort those values in increasing order before adding them to the answer.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
verticalOrderTraversal(root) {
    /* An empty tree has no vertical traversal */
    if root == null {

        /* Return an empty answer for this edge case */
        return {}
    }

    /* Store node values grouped by column and then by row */
    m = empty ordered map

    /* Start breadth-first traversal from the root at row 0 and column 0 */
    q = empty queue
    q.push({root, {0, 0}})

    /* Visit every node exactly once */
    while q is not empty {

        /* Take the current node and its position from the queue */
        cur = q.front().first
        row = q.front().second.first
        col = q.front().second.second
        q.pop()

        /* Save the current node inside its column and row group */
        m[col][row].push_back(cur->data)

        /* Move to the left child with updated row and column */
        if cur->left != null {

            /* The left child goes one row down and one column left */
            q.push({cur->left, {row + 1, col - 1}})
        }

        /* Move to the right child with updated row and column */
        if cur->right != null {

            /* The right child goes one row down and one column right */
            q.push({cur->right, {row + 1, col + 1}})
        }
    }

    /* Prepare the final answer column by column */
    ans = empty list

    /* Read columns from left to right */
    for each colEntry in m {

        /* Collect all values belonging to the current column */
        temp1 = empty list

        /* Read rows from top to bottom inside this column */
        for each rowEntry in colEntry.second {

            /* Sort values that share the same position */
            temp2 = rowEntry.second
            sort(temp2.begin(), temp2.end())

            /* Append the ordered values of this row to the current column */
            temp1.insert(temp1.end(), temp2.begin(), temp2.end())
        }

        /* Store the finished column in the answer */
        ans.push_back(temp1)
    }

    /* Return the complete vertical traversal */
    return ans
}
