# Flood Fill

## Depth-First Search

### Intuition

* We only need to change the connected region that has the same color as the starting cell.
* A natural idea is to begin from the starting cell and keep moving in the four allowed directions as long as the color stays the same.
* This works because every valid connected cell gets visited exactly once after it is recolored, although the recursion stack can grow large in the worst case.

### Approach

* Note the color present at the starting cell.
* If the starting color is already equal to the new color, return the image as it is.
* Start from the given cell and recolor it.
* Recursively move up, down, left, and right whenever the neighboring cell is inside the grid and has the original starting color.
* Return the updated image after the full connected region has been recolored.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
/* Fill the connected region starting from the given cell */
dfs(i, j, image, startingColor, newColor) {

    /* Store the number of rows for boundary checks */
    m = image.size()

    /* Store the number of columns for boundary checks */
    n = image[0].size()

    /* Recolor the current cell so it is marked as processed */
    image[i][j] = newColor

    /* Check the upper cell only if it is inside the grid and belongs to the same region */
    if i > 0 && image[i - 1][j] == startingColor {

        /* Continue filling through the upper neighbor */
        dfs(i - 1, j, image, startingColor, newColor)
    }

    /* Check the lower cell only if it is inside the grid and belongs to the same region */
    if i + 1 < m && image[i + 1][j] == startingColor {

        /* Continue filling through the lower neighbor */
        dfs(i + 1, j, image, startingColor, newColor)
    }

    /* Check the left cell only if it is inside the grid and belongs to the same region */
    if j > 0 && image[i][j - 1] == startingColor {

        /* Continue filling through the left neighbor */
        dfs(i, j - 1, image, startingColor, newColor)
    }

    /* Check the right cell only if it is inside the grid and belongs to the same region */
    if j + 1 < n && image[i][j + 1] == startingColor {

        /* Continue filling through the right neighbor */
        dfs(i, j + 1, image, startingColor, newColor)
    }
}

/* Start flood fill from the given position */
floodFill(image, r, c, newColor) {

    /* Store the original color of the starting cell */
    startingColor = image[r][c]

    /* If the starting cell already has the target color, no work is needed */
    if newColor == startingColor {

        /* Return the image unchanged */
        return image
    }

    /* Begin the recursive fill from the starting cell */
    dfs(r, c, image, startingColor, newColor)

    /* Return the updated image after filling is complete */
    return image
}
```

