# Number of Enclaves

## Solution

### Intuition

* A land cell is not part of the answer if we can reach it from any boundary land cell.
* So instead of checking every land cell separately, we first mark all land connected to the boundary.
* Whatever land remains unmarked after that must be fully enclosed by sea, so counting those cells gives the answer.

### Approach

* Create a separate grid to keep track of visited land cells.
* Start a depth-first search from every land cell on the boundary and mark all connected land cells.
* After all boundary-connected land is marked, scan only the inner part of the grid.
* Count the land cells that are still unvisited, because those are the enclaves.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
/* Mark all land cells connected to the current border land cell */
dfs(r, c, grid, visited) {

    /* Store the number of rows to keep boundary checks simple */
    m = grid.size()

    /* Store the number of columns to keep boundary checks simple */
    n = grid[0].size()

    /* Mark the current land cell so it is not processed again */
    visited[r][c] = 1

    /* Move upward only when the next cell is valid, unvisited, and land */
    if r > 0 && visited[r - 1][c] == 0 && grid[r - 1][c] == 1 {
        dfs(r - 1, c, grid, visited)
    }

    /* Move downward only when the next cell is valid, unvisited, and land */
    if r + 1 < m && visited[r + 1][c] == 0 && grid[r + 1][c] == 1 {
        dfs(r + 1, c, grid, visited)
    }

    /* Move left only when the next cell is valid, unvisited, and land */
    if c > 0 && visited[r][c - 1] == 0 && grid[r][c - 1] == 1 {
        dfs(r, c - 1, grid, visited)
    }

    /* Move right only when the next cell is valid, unvisited, and land */
    if c + 1 < n && visited[r][c + 1] == 0 && grid[r][c + 1] == 1 {
        dfs(r, c + 1, grid, visited)
    }

    /* All connected land cells for this path have been marked */
    return
}

/* Count all land cells that cannot reach the boundary */
numberOfEnclaves(grid) {

    /* Store the number of rows in the grid */
    m = grid.size()

    /* Store the number of columns in the grid */
    n = grid[0].size()

    /* Create a visited matrix to track land connected to the boundary */
    visited[m][n] = {0}

    /* Check every cell on the top and bottom borders */
    for j = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Start marking from the top border when the cell is land and unvisited */
        if grid[0][j] == 1 && visited[0][j] == 0 {
            dfs(0, j, grid, visited)
        }

        /* Start marking from the bottom border when the cell is land and unvisited */
        if grid[m - 1][j] == 1 && visited[m - 1][j] == 0 {
            dfs(m - 1, j, grid, visited)
        }
    }

    /* Check every cell on the left and right borders */
    for i = 0 to m - 1 {

        /* Start marking from the left border when the cell is land and unvisited */
        if grid[i][0] == 1 && visited[i][0] == 0 {
            dfs(i, 0, grid, visited)
        }

        /* Start marking from the right border when the cell is land and unvisited */
        if grid[i][n - 1] == 1 && visited[i][n - 1] == 0 {
            dfs(i, n - 1, grid, visited)
        }
    }

    /* Start the enclave count from zero */
    count = 0

    /* Only inner cells can be enclaves, so skip the boundary */
    for i = 1 to m - 2 {

        /* Scan every inner column of the current row */
        for j = 1 to n - 2 {

            /* Count land cells that were never reached from any boundary land */
            if visited[i][j] == 0 && grid[i][j] == 1 {
                count = count + 1
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the total number of enclave land cells */
    return count
}
