# Rotting Oranges

## Solution

### Intuition

* All rotten oranges spread their effect at the same speed, so every initially rotten orange should start spreading at the same time.
* The rot moves only to the four neighboring cells, which makes this a level-by-level traversal problem.
* Breadth-first search is a natural fit here because each level represents one minute of spreading.
* If any fresh orange is never reached during this process, then it can never become rotten.

### Approach

* Add all initially rotten oranges to a queue and treat them as starting points at time zero.
* Process the queue one state at a time and check the four neighboring cells of each rotten orange.
* When a fresh neighboring orange is found, mark it as visited, add it to the queue, and assign it one more minute than the current orange.
* Keep updating the answer with the latest minute seen during the traversal.
* After the queue becomes empty, scan the grid once more and return negative one if any fresh orange is still unreached; otherwise return the stored answer.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
rottenOranges(matrix) {
    /* Store the number of rows so we can stay within the grid */
    m = matrix.size()

    /* Store the number of columns so we can check neighbors safely */
    n = matrix[0].size()

    /* Keep track of which cells have already been processed */
    visited[m][n] = {0}

    /* Use a queue to spread the rot level by level */
    queue q

    /* Find every initially rotten orange and use it as a starting point */
    for i = 0 to m - 1 {

        /* Scan each column in the current row */
        for j = 0 to n - 1 {

            /* Only rotten oranges should enter the queue at time 0 */
            if matrix[i][j] == 2 {

                /* Store its position along with the time it is rotten */
                q.push({{i, j}, 0})

                /* Mark it so we do not process it again */
                visited[i][j] = 1
            }
        }
    }

    /* Store the minimum time needed to rot all reachable fresh oranges */
    ans_t = 0

    /* Continue until there are no more rotten oranges left to process */
    while !q.empty() {

        /* Read the front state from the queue */
        front = q.front()

        /* Extract the current row */
        r = front.first.first

        /* Extract the current column */
        c = front.first.second

        /* Extract the current time */
        t = front.second

        /* Update the answer with the latest time seen so far */
        ans_t = max(ans_t, t)

        /* Remove the processed state from the queue */
        q.pop()

        /* Check the top neighbor because it may become rotten next */
        if r > 0 && matrix[r - 1][c] == 1 && !visited[r - 1][c] {

            /* Add the top neighbor with one extra minute */
            q.push({{r - 1, c}, t + 1})

            /* Mark the top neighbor as visited */
            visited[r - 1][c] = 1
        }

        /* Check the bottom neighbor because it may become rotten next */
        if r + 1 < m && matrix[r + 1][c] == 1 && !visited[r + 1][c] {

            /* Add the bottom neighbor with one extra minute */
            q.push({{r + 1, c}, t + 1})

            /* Mark the bottom neighbor as visited */
            visited[r + 1][c] = 1
        }

        /* Check the left neighbor because it may become rotten next */
        if c > 0 && matrix[r][c - 1] == 1 && !visited[r][c - 1] {

            /* Add the left neighbor with one extra minute */
            q.push({{r, c - 1}, t + 1})

            /* Mark the left neighbor as visited */
            visited[r][c - 1] = 1
        }

        /* Check the right neighbor because it may become rotten next */
        if c + 1 < n && matrix[r][c + 1] == 1 && !visited[r][c + 1] {

            /* Add the right neighbor with one extra minute */
            q.push({{r, c + 1}, t + 1})

            /* Mark the right neighbor as visited */
            visited[r][c + 1] = 1
        }
    }

    /* Verify that no fresh orange was left unreached */
    for i = 0 to m - 1 {

        /* Scan every column in the current row */
        for j = 0 to n - 1 {

            /* A fresh orange that was never visited can never rot */
            if matrix[i][j] == 1 && !visited[i][j] {

                /* Return failure because not all oranges can become rotten */
                return -1
            }
        }
    }

    /* All fresh oranges were reached, so return the minimum time */
    return ans_t
}
