# Nearest Zero

## Solution

### Intuition

* Every cell needs the shortest distance to any zero, so starting a separate search from each cell would repeat a lot of work.
* A better idea is to start from all zero cells together and spread outward level by level.
* Since breadth-first search always reaches a cell in the fewest number of steps first, the first distance assigned to each cell is its answer.

### Approach

* Create a result grid to store the shortest distance for every cell.
* Mark all zero cells as already visited and put them into the queue with distance zero.
* Process the queue one cell at a time and try moving in all four directions.
* Whenever an unvisited neighbour is found, mark it visited, give it one more distance than the current cell, and push it into the queue.
* Continue until all reachable cells are processed, then return the result grid.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
nearestZero(grid) {

    /* Find the dimensions so we can build helper structures of the same size */
    m = grid.size()
    n = grid[0].size()

    /* Store the final shortest distance for every cell */
    ans[m][n] = {0}

    /* Prevent revisiting cells after their shortest distance is fixed */
    visited[m][n] = {0}

    /* Start breadth-first search from every zero cell together */
    queue q

    /* Scan the full grid and insert all zero cells as starting points */
    for i = 0 to m - 1 {

        /* Check every column in the current row */
        for j = 0 to n - 1 {

            /* Zero cells are the sources, so they begin with distance zero */
            if grid[i][j] == 0 {

                /* Push the zero cell into the queue with distance zero */
                q.push({{i, j}, 0})

                /* Mark this source as visited immediately */
                visited[i][j] = 1
            }
        }
    }

    /* Process cells in increasing order of distance from the nearest zero */
    while !q.empty() {

        /* Read the row of the current cell */
        r = q.front().first.first

        /* Read the column of the current cell */
        c = q.front().first.second

        /* Read the distance already computed for this cell */
        d = q.front().second

        /* Remove the current cell because it is now being processed */
        q.pop()

        /* Store the shortest distance for the current cell */
        ans[r][c] = d

        /* Visit the upper neighbour if it is inside the grid and not seen before */
        if r > 0 && !visited[r - 1][c] {

            /* Its distance is one more than the current cell */
            q.push({{r - 1, c}, d + 1})

            /* Mark it visited so it is added only once */
            visited[r - 1][c] = 1
        }

        /* Visit the lower neighbour if it is inside the grid and not seen before */
        if r + 1 < m && !visited[r + 1][c] {

            /* Its distance is one more than the current cell */
            q.push({{r + 1, c}, d + 1})

            /* Mark it visited so it is added only once */
            visited[r + 1][c] = 1
        }

        /* Visit the left neighbour if it is inside the grid and not seen before */
        if c > 0 && !visited[r][c - 1] {

            /* Its distance is one more than the current cell */
            q.push({{r, c - 1}, d + 1})

            /* Mark it visited so it is added only once */
            visited[r][c - 1] = 1
        }

        /* Visit the right neighbour if it is inside the grid and not seen before */
        if c + 1 < n && !visited[r][c + 1] {

            /* Its distance is one more than the current cell */
            q.push({{r, c + 1}, d + 1})

            /* Mark it visited so it is added only once */
            visited[r][c + 1] = 1
        }
    }

    /* All cells now store their shortest distance to a zero */
    return ans
