# Number of Distinct Islands

## Solution

### Intuition

* Two islands are considered the same only if one can be shifted to match the other without rotating or flipping it.
* So, instead of storing the actual cell positions, we store every land cell relative to the first cell of that island.
* If two islands produce the same relative pattern, they have the same shape. Using a set helps count only unique shapes.

### Approach

* Traverse every cell of the grid and start a depth-first search whenever an unvisited land cell is found.
* Mark each visited land cell so the same island is not explored again.
* While exploring one island, store the position of each cell relative to that island’s starting cell.
* After finishing that island, add its recorded shape to a set.
* Once the full grid is processed, return the number of unique shapes stored in the set.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
dfs(sr, sc, r, c, v, grid, visited) {
    /* Get the number of rows so boundary checks stay valid */
    m = grid.size()

    /* Get the number of columns so boundary checks stay valid */
    n = grid[0].size()

    /* Mark the current cell as visited so it is not explored again */
    visited[r][c] = 1

    /* Store the current cell using its offset from the island's starting cell */
    v.push_back({r - sr, c - sc})

    /* Move upward only when the next cell is inside the grid, is land, and is not visited */
    if r > 0 and grid[r - 1][c] == 1 and visited[r - 1][c] == 0 {

        /* Continue exploring the same island from the upper cell */
        dfs(sr, sc, r - 1, c, v, grid, visited)
    }

    /* Move downward only when the next cell is inside the grid, is land, and is not visited */
    if r + 1 < m and grid[r + 1][c] == 1 and visited[r + 1][c] == 0 {

        /* Continue exploring the same island from the lower cell */
        dfs(sr, sc, r + 1, c, v, grid, visited)
    }

    /* Move left only when the next cell is inside the grid, is land, and is not visited */
    if c > 0 and grid[r][c - 1] == 1 and visited[r][c - 1] == 0 {

        /* Continue exploring the same island from the left cell */
        dfs(sr, sc, r, c - 1, v, grid, visited)
    }

    /* Move right only when the next cell is inside the grid, is land, and is not visited */
    if c + 1 < n and grid[r][c + 1] == 1 and visited[r][c + 1] == 0 {

        /* Continue exploring the same island from the right cell */
        dfs(sr, sc, r, c + 1, v, grid, visited)
    }
}

distinctIslands(grid) {
    /* Store the number of rows for grid traversal */
    m = grid.size()

    /* Store the number of columns for grid traversal */
    n = grid[0].size()

    /* Create a visited matrix so every land cell is processed only once */
    visited = matrix of size m x n filled with 0

    /* Store all unique island shapes */
    s = empty set

    /* Check every row as a possible starting point of an island */
    for i = 0 to m - 1 {

        /* Check every column in the current row */
        for j = 0 to n - 1 {

            /* Start a new island traversal only from unvisited land */
            if grid[i][j] == 1 and visited[i][j] == 0 {

                /* Store the relative shape of the current island */
                v = empty list

                /* Explore the full island and record its shape */
                dfs(i, j, i, j, v, grid, visited)

                /* Add the discovered shape so duplicate islands collapse into one entry */
                s.insert(v)
            }
        }
    }

    /* The number of stored unique shapes is the answer */
    return s.size()
}
