# Safe Nodes

## Solution

### Intuition

* A node is safe only if every path starting from it eventually stops at a node with no outgoing edges.
* The only way a node becomes unsafe is when at least one path from it enters a cycle.
* So, for each node, we can run depth-first search and check whether we ever come back to a node already in the current path.
* To avoid repeating the same work, we remember whether a node was already proven safe or unsafe.

### Approach

* Keep a state for each node to show whether it is unvisited, currently being explored, already known to be safe, or already known to be unsafe.
* Run depth-first search from each node and explore all of its outgoing edges.
* If the search reaches a node that is already in the current recursion path, a cycle is found, so that path is unsafe.
* If any outgoing edge leads to an unsafe path, mark the current node as unsafe as well.
* If all outgoing edges lead only to safe nodes, mark the current node as safe and add it to the answer.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
dfs(curr, adj, state) {
    /* If this node is already in the current recursion path, a cycle is found */
    if state[curr] == 1 {
        /* This path is unsafe because it reaches a cycle */
        return false
    }

    /* If this node was already confirmed safe, reuse that result */
    if state[curr] == 2 {
        /* No need to explore again */
        return true
    }

    /* If this node was already confirmed unsafe, reuse that result */
    if state[curr] == 3 {
        /* This node cannot be part of the answer */
        return false
    }

    /* Mark the current node as being explored in the current path */
    state[curr] = 1

    /* Explore every outgoing edge from the current node */
    for each k in adj[curr] {

        /* If any next node leads to an unsafe path, current node is also unsafe */
        if dfs(k, adj, state) == false {

            /* Store that this node is unsafe for future calls */
            state[curr] = 3

            /* Return failure immediately because one bad path is enough */
            return false
        }
    }

    /* All outgoing paths were safe, so mark this node as safe */
    state[curr] = 2

    /* Return success because every path ends safely */
    return true
}

safeNodes(adj) {
    /* Store the total number of nodes in the graph */
    n = adj.size()

    /* State values: 0 = unvisited, 1 = visiting, 2 = safe, 3 = unsafe */
    state[n] = {0}

    /* Create the answer list for all safe nodes */
    ans = {}

    /* Check every node in ascending order */
    for i from 0 to n - 1 {

        /* If the current node is safe, include it in the result */
        if dfs(i, adj, state) == true {

            /* Add this safe node to the answer */
            ans.push_back(i)
        }
    }

    /* Return the safe nodes in ascending order */
    return ans
}
