# Shortest Path in DAG

## Solution

### Intuition

* Since the graph has no cycles, we can process vertices in an order where every directed edge goes forward.
* Once a vertex is processed in that order, we can safely use its current shortest distance to improve the distances of all vertices reachable from it.
* This lets us find shortest paths in one pass after building that order, instead of repeatedly relaxing edges like in general graphs.
* Any vertex that is never reached from the source simply stays unreachable, so its answer becomes `-1`.

### Approach

* Build an adjacency list to store every directed edge along with its weight.
* Run a depth first traversal from the source and push each vertex after exploring all of its outgoing edges.
* This stack gives the reachable vertices in topological order when popped.
* Start with distance `0` for the source and a very large value for every other vertex.
* Pop vertices one by one and relax all outgoing edges to update shorter distances.
* Replace every still-unreachable distance with `-1` at the end.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
dfs(node, visited, adj, s) {
    /* Mark the current vertex so it is not visited again */
    visited[node] = 1

    /* Explore all outgoing edges from the current vertex */
    for each k in adj[node] {

        /* Read the next connected vertex */
        neighbour = k.first

        /* Visit the neighbour first if it has not been explored yet */
        if visited[neighbour] == 0 {

            /* Continue depth first traversal from the neighbour */
            dfs(neighbour, visited, adj, s)
        }
    }

    /* Push the current vertex after exploring all reachable paths from it */
    s.push(node)
}

shortestPath(n, e, edges) {
    /* Create a visited array to build the processing order */
    visited[n] = {0}

    /* Prepare the adjacency list for the graph */
    adj = list of n empty lists

    /* Insert every directed weighted edge into the adjacency list */
    for i = 0 to e - 1 {

        /* Extract the current edge information */
        a = edges[i][0]
        b = edges[i][1]
        weight = edges[i][2]

        /* Store the destination and weight for this edge */
        adj[a].push({b, weight})
    }

    /* Create a stack to store vertices in finishing order */
    s = empty stack

    /* Start traversal from the source because only reachable vertices matter */
    dfs(0, visited, adj, s)

    /* Initialize all distances as unreachable */
    dist[n] = {INT_MAX}

    /* Distance to the source itself is zero */
    dist[0] = 0

    /* Process vertices in topological order */
    while s is not empty {

        /* Take the next vertex from the stack */
        curr = s.top()
        s.pop()

        /* Relax outgoing edges only if the current vertex is reachable */
        if dist[curr] != INT_MAX {

            /* Try to improve the distance of every neighbour */
            for each k in adj[curr] {

                /* Read the neighbour and edge weight */
                neighbour = k.first
                weight = k.second

                /* Update the distance if a shorter path is found */
                if dist[curr] + weight < dist[neighbour] {

                    /* Save the better distance */
                    dist[neighbour] = dist[curr] + weight
                }
            }
        }
    }

    /* Convert unreachable values into the required answer format */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Mark vertices that cannot be reached from the source */
        if dist[i] == INT_MAX {

            /* Replace infinity with minus one */
            dist[i] = -1
        }
    }

    /* Return the final shortest distances */
    return dist
}
