# Shortest Path in Undirected Graph

## Solution

### Intuition

* Every edge has the same cost, so the shortest path depends only on how many edges we use.
* This means we should explore all nodes at distance one first, then distance two, and so on.
* Breadth-first search does exactly that, so the first time we reach a node, we have already found its shortest distance.

### Approach

* Build an adjacency list so each vertex knows all directly connected vertices.
* Start from the given source vertex, mark it as visited, and set its distance to zero.
* Use a queue to explore vertices level by level.
* Whenever an unvisited neighbor is found, mark it visited, assign it one more than the current distance, and add it to the queue.
* Keep unreachable vertices unchanged as minus one.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```plaintext
/* Find the shortest distance from the start vertex to every other vertex */
shortestPath(n, e, edges, start) {

    /* Create an adjacency list with one empty list for each vertex */
    adj = n empty lists

    /* Build the undirected graph from the given edge list */
    for i = 0 to e - 1 {

        /* Read both endpoints of the current edge */
        a = edges[i][0]
        b = edges[i][1]

        /* Add the connection in both directions */
        adj[a].push_back(b)
        adj[b].push_back(a)
    }

    /* Create a queue to process vertices in breadth-first order */
    q = empty queue

    /* Start the traversal from the source vertex */
    q.push(start)

    /* Mark all vertices as unvisited at the beginning */
    visited = array of size n filled with 0

    /* Mark the source vertex as visited so it is not processed again */
    visited[start] = 1

    /* Store shortest distances and begin with all vertices unreachable */
    dist = array of size n filled with -1

    /* Distance from the source vertex to itself is zero */
    dist[start] = 0

    /* Continue until every reachable vertex has been processed */
    while q is not empty {

        /* Take the next vertex from the front of the queue */
        curr = q.front()

        /* Remove the processed vertex from the queue */
        q.pop()

        /* Explore every neighbor of the current vertex */
        for each k in adj[curr] {

            /* Visit the neighbor only the first time it is discovered */
            if visited[k] == 0 {

                /* Its shortest distance is one more than the current vertex */
                dist[k] = dist[curr] + 1

                /* Mark the neighbor as visited to avoid repeated work */
                visited[k] = 1

                /* Add the neighbor to the queue for further exploration */
                q.push(k)
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the final shortest distance array */
    return dist
}
